\chapter{DSP Workshops}

Leeds Beckett University DSP workshops

\section{Accessing Jupyter Workbooks}

The lab workstations and servers provide two environments for running
Jupyter workbooks

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \href{https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/datascience/jupyter-notebooks}{Microsoft
  Visual Studio Code}
\item
  \href{https://jupyter.org/}{Jupyter Lab}
\end{itemize}

Unless you are running complex code, Visual Studio Code is the simplest
to set-up. If you are running complex code, including that requiring
significant GPU resources, the School also provides access to

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \href{https://jupyterhub.aet.leedsbeckett.ac.uk/}{Jupyter Hub}
\end{itemize}

Whatever you intend to run you will need to ensure Python is setup
correctly

\section{Python Setup}

\subsection{Libraries}

Different versions of \texttt{Pandas} and \texttt{Matplotlib} have
slightly different features, and in some cases don't work in quite the
same way as previous versions. To avoid frustration, these workshops
have been developed with the following major versions as a minimum

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \href{https://matplotlib.org/}{\texttt{Matplotlib}}: 3.9
\item
  \href{https://numpy.org/}{\texttt{NumPy}}: 1.26
\item
  \href{https://pandas.pydata.org/}{\texttt{Pandas}}: 1.5
\item
  \href{https://www.python.org/downloads/}{\texttt{Python}}: 3.12
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Using Conda}

All of the core and recommended packages are available on the lab
workstations and server environments. Access is easiest via
\href{https://anaconda.org/anaconda/conda}{conda}, which provides a
mechanism to create a controlled virtual Python environment. You can
either install the full
\href{https://docs.conda.io/projects/conda/en/latest/index.html}{Conda}
package, or use
\href{https://www.anaconda.com/docs/getting-started/miniconda/install}{Miniconda}
on most platforms.

Whichever package you use, they should all provide the \texttt{conda}
utility as the main interface. Using the \texttt{conda} utility, the
Workbooks can all be run using a suitable \texttt{environment.yml} as
below

\begin{verbatim}
name: DSP
 
channels:
  - default
dependencies:
  - ipywidgets
  - jupyterlab>=4.2
  - jupyterlab_widgets
  - matplotlib>=3.9
  - numpy>=1.26
  - scipy>=1.14
  - pandas>=1.5
  - seaborn>=0.3
\end{verbatim}

When you cloned the git repository you will see it includes the above in
a file called \texttt{environment.yaml}. Conda can use the
\texttt{environment.yaml} to create a `\texttt{DSP}' environment by
running the following in a terminal window (or a Terminal Tab on Jupyter
Hub)

\begin{verbatim}
conda env create -f environment.yml
\end{verbatim}

\subsubsection{Lab workstations (PCs)}

If working on a Lab workstation (i.e.~directly on a computer) then you
can check the environment has been sucessfully created by running

\begin{verbatim}
conda info --envs
\end{verbatim}

This should show the \texttt{DSP} environment. Once found, the
environment can be activated through the command

\begin{verbatim}
conda activate DSP
\end{verbatim}

Development environments such as Visual Studio Code also have
\href{https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/python/environments}{direct
support}
\href{https://www.anaconda.com/docs/tools/working-with-conda/ide-tutorials/vscode}{for
Conda}.

\subsubsection{Jupyter Hub}

Having created the instance you will need to init the environment and
then activate it:

\begin{verbatim}
conda init
source ~/.bashrc
conda activate DSP
\end{verbatim}

If you are coming back to Jupyter Hub then the commands to activate the
exisiting environemnt are:

\begin{verbatim}
source ~/.bashrc
conda activate DSP
\end{verbatim}

